		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper13</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Towards a taxonomy of grammar smells</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MatsStijlaart.html">Mats Stijlaart</a>, <a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136035">10.1145/3136014.3136035</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a taxonomy of grammar smells, i.e., systematic analysis of grammar/language descriptions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t2b.html"><span class="tagL">T2B: Evolution</span></a><ul><li> Grammar smells are motivated by grammar refactoring and maintenance of evolving language definitions.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The objects analyzed are grammars, which are meta-language artifacts used to define syntax.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> A taxonomy supports building analysis/refactoring tools for grammars, which the paper discusses as a motivation.
</li></ul></li></ul>
